[30;1m109 | [0m[35m- **Flexible**: Pyro aims for automation when you want it, control when you need it. This is accompl[0m
[30;1m110 | [0m[35m[0m

[30;1m580 | [0m[35m    This model also adds an optional likelihood for observed phylogenetic data[0m
[30;1m581 | [0m[35m    in the form of coalescent times. These are provided as a pair[0m
[30;1m582 | [0m[35m    ``(leaf_times, coal_times)`` of times at which genomes are sequenced and[0m
[30;1m583 | [0m[35m    lineages coalesce, respectively. We incorporate this data using the[0m

[30;1m159 | [0m[35m            represent the training data that are conditioned on for the purpose of making[0m

[30;1m513 | [0m[35mdef energy_score_empirical(pred: torch.Tensor, truth: torch.Tensor) -> torch.Tensor:[0m
[30;1m514 | [0m[35m    """[0m
[30;1m515 | [0m[35m    Computes negative Energy Score ES* (see equation 22 in [1]) between a[0m
[30;1m516 | [0m[35m    set of multivariate samples ``pred`` and a true data vector ``truth``. Running time[0m
[30;1m517 | [0m[35m    is quadratic in the number of samples ``n``. In case of univariate samples[0m
[30;1m518 | [0m[35m    the output coincides with the CRPS::[0m
[30;1m519 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m520 | [0m[35m        ES* = E|pred - truth| - 1/2 E|pred - pred'|[0m

[30;1m501 | [0m[35m        return (pred[0] - truth).abs()[0m
[30;1m502 | [0m[35m[0m
[30;1m503 | [0m[35m    pred = pred.sort(dim=0).values[0m
[30;1m504 | [0m[35m    diff = pred[1:] - pred[:-1][0m
[30;1m505 | [0m[35m    weight = torch.arange(1, num_samples, **opts) * torch.arange([0m

[30;1m164 | [0m[35m        detH = H[..., 0, 0] * H[..., 1, 1] - H[..., 0, 1] * H[..., 1, 0][0m
[30;1m165 | [0m[35m        mean_eig = (H[..., 0, 0] + H[..., 1, 1]) / 2[0m
[30;1m166 | [0m[35m        min_eig = mean_eig - (mean_eig**2 - detH).clamp(min=0).sqrt()[0m

[30;1m385 | [0m[35m    This uses Gibbs sampling on edges. Consider E undirected edges that can[0m
[30;1m386 | [0m[35m    move around a graph of ``V=1+E`` vertices. The edges are constrained so[0m
[30;1m387 | [0m[35m    that no two edges can span the same pair of vertices and so that the edges[0m
[30;1m388 | [0m[35m    must form a spanning tree. To Gibbs sample, chose one of the E edges at[0m
[30;1m389 | [0m[35m    random and move it anywhere else in the graph. After we remove the edge,[0m
[30;1m390 | [0m[35m    notice that the graph is split into two connected components. The[0m
[30;1m391 | [0m[35m    constraints imply that the edge must be replaced so as to connect the two[0m
[30;1m392 | [0m[35m    components.  Hence to Gibbs sample, we collect all such bridging[0m
